<HEADLINE>
<P>
OLD FRIEND LOVULLO WEARS A DIFFERENT CAP; BASEBALL: FORMER ANGEL INFIELDER WAS 
CALLED UP BY THE MARINERS JUST IN TIME FOR A VISIT TO ANAHEIM STADIUM. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELLIOTT TEAFORD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Torey Lovullo walked into familiar surroundings this week at Anaheim Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
 But instead of heading for the home team's clubhouse, as he had so many times 
before, he went through the doors marked "Visitors." 
</P>
<P>
 Once inside, he pulled on the gray pants and blue practice jersey of the 
Seattle Mariners, slipped on a cap with an 'S' on it and headed to the field. 
</P>
<P>
 His work day was just beginning, but waves of emotion had already started 
rolling over him. This was his first game back in the major leagues and his 
first day back at Anaheim Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
 Lovullo, 29, was an Angel for only one season, but memories and friendships 
die hard. Heck, Prime Ticket almost nightly runs a tape of Lovullo hurling his 
batting helmet into the air after his hit beat the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
 J.T. Snow, Lovullo's best friend on the Angels and his roommate when they were 
members of the Yankee organization, is the enemy now, along with other buddies 
such as Gary DiSarcina and Chad Curtis. 
</P>
<P>
 "The visitors' locker room is the other way," Angel pitcher Russ Springer 
said, cracking a smile when he spotted Lovullo in the hallway leading to the 
clubhouses. 
</P>
<P>
 "Russell, how are you?" Lovullo said, shaking Springer's hand. 
</P>
<P>
 "My best friends in the game are on that team," Lovullo had told a reporter 
earlier. "It was hard. I had talked to J.T. on the phone. Now, seeing them all 
together, that was strange. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm just glad to be back home in Anaheim. I'm excited. I want to stick it to 
(the Angels). I want to have the game on the line and do a number on them. 
There's going to be a lot of emotion." 
</P>
<P>
 Lovullo, from UCLA, played in 116 major league games last year, a career-high, 
batting .251 with six home runs and 30 runs batted in. They were modest numbers 
to be sure, but Lovullo's impact extended beyond statistics. 
</P>
<P>
 Two clutch hits stand out in the Angels' unexpectedly successful first half of 
'93. Each built excitement when none was expected. Without those sorts of 
contributions, the Angels this season have fallen into what seems to be an 
emotional abyss. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'd like to think they might be missing me," Lovullo said. "Obviously, 
they've gone in a different direction and didn't see a need for me." 
</P>
<P>
 The Angels released Lovullo during spring training, opting instead for Rex 
Hudler and Spike Owen as their utility infielders. Each has contributed, and 
Owen, playing a position other than shortstop for the first time in his career, 
has become the everyday third baseman. 
</P>
<P>
 Lovullo was stung by the move, but now says he only had himself to blame. 
After his first full season as a major league player, he said he eased up a 
little bit, didn't work as hard as usual over the winter. 
</P>
<P>
 Perhaps he fooled himself with his success. There were reasons to be content 
as an Angel. 
</P>
<P>
 In an early season game against Boston and Roger Clemens, Lovullo hit what 
turned out to be the game-winning homer in a 2-1 Angel victory. The Angels' 
postgame mood was joyous. 
</P>
<P>
 Then, on the day before the All-Star break, Lovullo's bases-loaded single in 
the 14th inning gave the Angels a 3-2 victory over the Yankees. It also pulled 
the Angels within two games of first place in the American League West. 
</P>
<P>
 You've probably seen the tape dozens of times by now, maybe without realizing 
what it was. Half running, half skipping, Lovullo rounded first base, tore off 
his helmet and chucked it into the sky. In a flash, he was mobbed by teammates. 
</P>
<P>
 Sports, L.A. style.  
</P>
<P>
 If there was a defining moment of the Angels' fast start, that was it. After 
the break, they faltered, unable to keep pace in the AL West. But Lovullo 
always hoped management would remember the good times of '93. 
</P>
<P>
 Near the end of spring training, the Angels cut him. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'll fault myself for the rest of my life," said Lovullo, who was claimed 
from the waiver wire by Seattle April 1. "I wasn't ready for spring training. I 
felt last year I would be ready without working the way I did before. I was 
kind of shocked. I knew they had to make a move, but (getting released) was the 
last thing on my mind." 
</P>
<P>
 Time has passed, but Lovullo can't forget his past as an Angel. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'd be lying if I said I didn't think a lot about last year," he said. "It's 
baseball. It's a business. (But) I had an awfully good time here last year." 
</P>
<P>
 This week proved to be another adventure in the business side of the game for 
Lovullo. Tuesday, he traded places with 19-year-old shortstop Alex Rodriguez, 
who was optioned to triple-A Calgary. It marks Lovullo's third stint in the 
major leagues this season. In 30 games so far, he has hit .213 with two homers 
and seven RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
 This visit to the majors, however, appears doomed by the expected players' 
strike, which is set to begin Aug. 12. 
</P>
<P>
 For now, Lovullo searches for his niche with the Mariners. When he was a 
member of the Detroit Tigers, Sparky Anderson said something to the effect that 
it would take an act of Congress to get Lovullo out of the lineup. 
</P>
<P>
 Several seasons have passed since then and Lovullo is still trying to hustle 
an everyday spot in a major league lineup. 
</P>
<P>
 "I miss the heck out of them," he said of his former teammates. "But you have 
to move on. I think I need to get in the lineup and show how I can play the 
game." 
</P>
</TEXT>
