<HEADLINE>
<P>
INSIDE LINE: OC HIGH: STUDENT NEWS AND VIEWS; A STATE OF MIND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Virginity is only a state of mind. 
</P>
<P>
 That's the message some New York City educators want to get across to sexually 
active teens: It's never too late to become a virgin.The name for the concept? 
Secondary virginity. 
</P>
<P>
 It's "a nice way of saying that even if you have been sleeping around for 
years, you can be clean again," one proponent said. 
</P>
<P>
 "What is wrong with telling a child that it's a good idea to stop (having 
sex)? That is what we promote for drugs," board of education advisory member 
Liliana Trivelli said. 
</P>
<P>
 But the board's student representative, Andrea Schlesinger, 17, said she 
doesn't think the idea will apply to most of her peers. 
</P>
<P>
 Secondary virginity implies that "you can make up for your mistake," 
Schlesinger, 17, said. "For many young people, it was not a mistake." 
</P>
</TEXT>
